  "prompt": "Which is the shortest completed cricket Test match?",
  "response": "The shortest completed Test match in cricket history took place between **Australia and South Africa** in **Durban**, from **March 21 to March 23, 1939**. This match concluded on the **second day**, making it the shortest Test in terms of days played.\n\n### Key Details:\n- **Teams:** Australia vs. South Africa\n- **Location:** Kingsmead Cricket Ground, Durban, South Africa\n- **Dates:** March 21-23, 1939\n- **Duration:** Completed on the **second day**\n- **Result:** Australia won by an innings and 149 runs\n\n### Match Summary:\nThe Australian team dominated the game from the outset. South Africa struggled with their batting lineup and were bowled out cheaply in both innings. Australia's batsmen capitalized on these weaknesses, leading to a swift and decisive victory. The match showcased the importance of strong opening performances and how quickly a Test match can conclude when one team is significantly superior.\n\n### Historical Significance:\nThis Test match stands out not just for its brevity but also as a reflection of the playing conditions and team strengths during that era. It remains a benchmark in Test cricket for the shortest duration, emphasizing how balance in the game can lead to quick results.\n\n---\n\n**Note:** Test matches are traditionally scheduled for five days, but various factors like weather conditions, pitch behavior, and team performances can lead to shorter conclusions.",
